   <note>Informs him of the writer`s progress in his attempt to secure letters of recommendation for the Marshalcy. Tells of the enragement of Memphis`s Ku Klux Klan because of the arrest of Earle and a week full of insults and danger for Union men. Describes incidents in which the writer and Lewis were involved and refers to Charlie`s fear and the need for martial law in Memphis. Touches on Horace`s plans to obtain the post of superintendent.</note>
